
                                             FINAL REPORT

This task involved deploying a secure, production-like Amazon RDS MySQL database in a private Multi-AZ setup with no public access, 
ensuring high availability and data protection. IAM database authentication was enabled so EC2 instances could securely access the database using 
temporary tokens instead of static credentials, while TLS-only enforcement ensured all connections were encrypted. 
Database credentials were managed using AWS Secrets Manager with automatic rotation configured through Lambda, improving security 
and reducing manual handling of sensitive data. The application EC2 instance was placed in a private subnet with an attached IAM role to retrieve 
authentication tokens dynamically and connect securely to the RDS instance. Backup and point-in-time recovery (PITR) were enabled and validated to ensure
the database could be restored within a minimal recovery window (RPO within 5 minutes), confirming reliable disaster recovery capability.
